diff:1619311392:1619311392:=1,58d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: Discriminatory 'Asian Style' Fonts%0a%3c :Author: jjmonroe%0a%3c :Section: C%0a%3c :Completed: 24.04.2021 - 17:43%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c The use of "chop suey fonts" to denote "Asianness" appropriate the style of other languages in a manner some find discriminatory%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c Trigger Warning: Although I have omitted it here, the source article contains a racist depiction of a Japanese person dating back to the World War 2 era.%0a%3c %0a%3c For decades, American establishments have been using fonts such as Wanton%0a%3c %0a%3c https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%253A%252F%252Fcdn.cnn.com%252Fcnnnext%252Fdam%252Fassets%252F210324163527-05-style-font-design-restricted.jpg%0a%3c %0a%3c to denote some sort of Asian affiliation. The usages of this style range from%0a%3c cases most people would deem relatively benign (albeit tinged with the prejudices of American society), such as Chinese immigrants using it on their own restaurants to differentiate their businesses and enhance their exotic appeal, to blatantly racist depictions of Asians in wartime propaganda. For many older Asian-Americans, this racist perception lingers, and seeing similar fonts recalls the anti-Asian signs of the past. Additionally, the fonts have been used to paint Asian political candidates in a negative light in attack ads.%0a%3c %0a%3c The linguistic tie-in to this discriminatory appropriation comes in the fact that  there is no real link between any structural elements of any Asian language. There is no understanding or appreciation for another language, just a bare ripping of the basic stylistic elements of traditional calligraphy. It is difficult to single out the linguistic properties present, simply because the appropriation is done without any interest whatsoever in the linguistic characteristics of the languages it draws from (this is even evident in the fact that it draws from "languages": languages like Japanese and Chinese are massively different and unique, and fonts like Wonton pull from them without any  discretion between them).%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Source:%0a%3c https://edition.cnn.com/style/article/chop-suey-fonts-hyphenated/index.html%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
